h3. Issue Summary

A word file containing any Shapes cannot be imported.


 !Screen Shot 2021-04-21 at 15.42.35.png|thumbnail! 
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a page
 # Try importing this file - [^file.docx] 
 # The below error occurs:
{code:none}
This file can't be imported
We ran into issues because the file may the wrong type, password protected, or read-only.
{code}


h3. Expected Results

The word file can be imported ignoring Shapes.

h3. Actual Results

HTTP status 400 error occurs at https://cc-import-s.services.atlassian.com/import/upload

{code:javascript}
{
	"error": {
		"type": "CorruptedDocumentError",
		"message": "Input document seems to be corrupted",
		"rootCause": "Cannot read property 'getAttribute' of undefined"
	}
}
{code}


h3. Workaround

Remove *Shapes* from the Word file.
Consider adding yourself as a watcher to be kept informed as to the state of this feature request moving forward. With that way, if our development team updates the ticket, you'll be notified via email.

h3. Summary

At present the API /wiki/rest/api/space/KEY?expand=permissions doesnt give results for ALL>>Delete Own, PAGE >>archive and MAIL>>Delete
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Open a browser tab
 # Add a JSON viewer extension from the web store
 # Add a set of permissions on the UI end of the space.
 # Use this API [https://sitename.atlassian.net/wiki/rest/api/space/spacekey?expand=permissions] to get the space permissions.
 # It should all the permissions parameter i.e all 15 in space permissions.
 # Currently, this API will only give 12 operations excluding ALL>>Delete Own, PAGE >>archive and MAIL>>Delete
 !screenshot-1.png|thumbnail! 
 *Browser Console*
{code:java}
function main() {
    const getData = async () => {
        const url = 'https://<SITENAME>.atlassian.net/wiki/rest/api/space/<SPACEKEY>?expand=permissions';
        const response = await fetch(url).then((r) => (r.json()));
        response.permissions.forEach(ele => {console.log(ele.operation)})
    };
    getData();
}
main();
{code}
*Outcome*
{code:java}
{operation: "restrict_content", targetType: "space"}
VM1098:5 {operation: "create", targetType: "attachment"}
VM1098:5 {operation: "delete", targetType: "page"}
VM1098:5 {operation: "export", targetType: "space"}
VM1098:5 {operation: "create", targetType: "comment"}
VM1098:5 {operation: "create", targetType: "blogpost"}
VM1098:5 {operation: "delete", targetType: "comment"}
VM1098:5 {operation: "delete", targetType: "blogpost"}
VM1098:5 {operation: "delete", targetType: "attachment"}
VM1098:5 {operation: "create", targetType: "page"}
VM1098:5 {operation: "administer", targetType: "space"}
VM1098:5 {operation: "read", targetType: "space"}
{code}

It's not showing Archive, Delete Own, and Mail delete permissions
h3. Suggestion

For Users to inspect and see consolidated space permissions, it's good to include all 15 operations when using API.

h3. Issue Summary

When we paste an anchor or header link to a page creates static links instead of dynamic ones.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # +Create+ a new page called *Page A*.
 # +Create+ a new page called *Page B*.
 # On the *Page B* create a +header and an anchor+.
 # On the *Page A* +create a link to the header and anchor+ from *Page B*.

(!) If you export those pages to HTML the links are static and point to the web instead of the html links.
h3. Expected Results

Create dynamic links using {{ac:link}} instead of {{href}}:
{code:html}
<ac:link ac:card-appearance="inline"><ri:page ri:content-title="Page B#Anchor" ri:version-at-save="X" /><ac:link-body>Page B</ac:link-body></ac:link>{code}
OR
{code:html}
<ac:link ac:card-appearance="inline"><ri:page ri:content-title="Page B#Header" ri:version-at-save="X" /><ac:link-body>Page B</ac:link-body></ac:link>{code}
h3. Actual Results

It creates the following static links using {{href}} instead of {{ac:link}}:
{code:html}
<a href="https://<SITENAME>.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/<SPACKEY>/pages/<CONTENTID>/Page+B#Anchor" data-card-appearance="inline"><SITENAME>.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/<SPACKEY>/pages/<CONTENTID>/Page+B#Anchor</a>{code}
OR
{code:html}
<a href="https://<SITENAME>.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/<SPACKEY>/pages/<CONTENTID>/Page+B#Header" data-card-appearance="inline"><SITENAME>.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/<SPACKEY>/pages/<CONTENTID>/Page+B#Header</a>{code}
h3. Workaround

Currently, there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available.

h3. Issue Summary

Connect Apps can create [custom content|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/confluence/modules/custom-content/], which can implement their own [containment model|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/confluence/working-with-custom-content-children/]. In addition, custom content can opt into [search indexing|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/confluence/searching-custom-content/]. When all of these are enabled, CQL should respect [the containment fields|https://developer.atlassian.com/server/confluence/cql-field-reference/] in CQL: {{ancestor}}, {{container}}, and {{parent}}.

h3. Steps to Reproduce

Given a connect descriptor with this custom content section:
{code:json}
...
    "customContent": [
      {
        "key": "question",
        "bodyType": "storage",
        "name": {
          "value": "Questions "
        },
        "apiSupport": {
          "supportedContainerTypes": [
            "space"
          ],
          "supportedSpacePermissions": [
            "read",
            "create",
            "delete"
          ],
          "supportedChildTypes": [
            "ac:questions-answers-for-confluence:answer",
            "ac:questions-answers-for-confluence:reaction",
            "comment",
            "attachment"
          ],
          "indexing": {
            "enabled": true
          }
        },
        "uiSupport": {
          "listViewComponent": {
            "moduleKey": "questionsView"
          },
          "contentViewComponent": {
            "moduleKey": "questionsView"
          },
          "icons": {
            "item": {
              "url": "/images/questions-black.svg"
            }
          }
        }
      },
      {
        "key": "answer",
        "name": {
          "value": "Answers"
        },
        "apiSupport": {
          "supportedContainerTypes": [
            "ac:questions-answers-for-confluence:question"
          ],
          "supportedChildTypes": [
            "ac:questions-answers-for-confluence:reaction",
            "comment",
            "attachment"
          ],
          "indexing": {
            "enabled": true
          }
        },
        "uiSupport": {
          "contentViewComponent": {
            "moduleKey": "questionsView"
          },
          "listViewComponent": {
            "moduleKey": "questionsView"
          },
          "icons": {
            "item": {
              "url": "/images/questions-black.svg"
            }
          }
        }
      },
      {
        "key": "reaction",
        "name": {
          "value": "Votes"
        },
        "apiSupport": {
          "supportedContainerTypes": [
            "ac:questions-answers-for-confluence:question",
            "ac:questions-answers-for-confluence:answer"
          ],
          "supportedSpacePermissions": [
            "read",
            "create",
            "delete"
          ],
          "indexing": {
            "enabled": true
          }
        },
        "uiSupport": {
          "contentViewComponent": {
            "moduleKey": "questionsView"
          },
          "listViewComponent": {
            "moduleKey": "questionsView"
          },
          "icons": {
            "item": {
              "url": "/images/questions-black.svg"
            }
          }
        }
      },
...
{code}

Then the App has the following hierarchies of custom content:
Question → has Answers → has Reactions and  Question → has Reactions.

In the data, we have:

* Question with ID = 633405478 being parent of two answers, one of them with Id = 635601068
* Answer with ID = 635601068 is a parent of 3 reactions with Ids = 1226571928, 635601089 and 633405653

What I want to search for is getting all reactions whose parent/container is answer with Id = 635601068. Given that, following CQL searches are not working as expected:

* type='ac:questions-answers-for-confluence:reaction' and container = 635601068: returns no results, should return 3 results with reactions above
* type='ac:questions-answers-for-confluence:reaction' and ancestor = 635601068: returns no results, should return 3 results with reactions above
* type='ac:questions-answers-for-confluence:reaction' and ancestor = 633405478: returns no results, should return at least 3 results with reactions above (I’m not interested in this kind of search because it’s too broad as I want to return only reactions with answer 635601068 as direct parent, but this search doesn’t work as expected as well)

Similar CQL search that does work (but doesn't help with my issue) is searching for answers based on question ID as container

* type='ac:questions-answers-for-confluence:answer' and container = 633405478: correctly returns 2 child answers

h3. Expected Results

All 3 CQL searches should return 3 results, according to the definitions of the CQL search fields.

h3. Actual Results

All 3 CQL searches return no results.

h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary

When performing a request to the /wiki/rest/api/group/member and paginating results, we'll get some duplicated values and some other values missing;
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Perform the following GET request:
{code:none}
/wiki/rest/api/group/member?name=confluence-users&limit=100&start=0{code}

 # Compare the results with the following request, repeated 10 times, increasing the start parameter by 10 each time:
{code:none}
/wiki/rest/api/group/member?name=confluence-users&limit=10&start=0{code}

h3. Expected Results

both methods should present the same results
h3. Actual Results

The second method will present the same number of results, but it includes duplicates and, consequently, missing entries.
h3. Workaround

At this moment, the only workaround is to avoid using pagination for the /wiki/rest/api/group/member endpoint.

h3. Issue Summary
An invalid CQL statement should return an error result. HTTP status 400 is fine. But the error it returns is misleading, which makes it hard for clients (Apps) to be resilient.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Use the CQL endpoint to search for something that doesn't match. For example, {{/wiki/rest/api/content/search?cql=🎶}}. Note, valid CQL requires some key/value pairs to match, so it's not the unicode that should make this invalid.

h3. Expected Results

The authorized section should be populated true (the client is authorized) and the errors array should indicate what went wrong. For example:

{code:json}
{
  "statusCode": 400,
  "data": {
    "authorized": true,
    "valid": true,
    "errors": ["Could not parse cql : 🎶"],
    "successful": false
  },
  "message": "com.atlassian.confluence.api.service.exceptions.BadRequestException: Could not parse cql : 🎶"
}
{code}


h3. Actual Results
The error incorrectly reports the client was not authorized and has no data that is semantically an error. The message portion must be parsed to understand the error.

{code:json}
{
  "statusCode": 400,
  "data": {
    "authorized": false,
    "valid": true,
    "errors": [],
    "successful": false
  },
  "message": "com.atlassian.confluence.api.service.exceptions.BadRequestException: Could not parse cql : 🎶"
}
{code}

h3. Workaround

 Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available.
